MDS¶

Using MDS on the large dataset (with the 0 values) resulted in the error: 'Unable to allocate 297. GiB for an array with shape (199523, 199523) and data type float64'. It is therefore to large for this method. I opted to filter the data according to the following code block:

In [ ]:
reduced_subsample_data = subsample_data[subsample_data['wage per hour'] > 0]
reduced_subsample_data = reduced_subsample_data[reduced_subsample_data['age'] > 18]
reduced_subsample_data = reduced_subsample_data[reduced_subsample_data['weeks worked in year'] > 30]
reduced_subsample_data.describe()

from sklearn.manifold import MDS
from sklearn.metrics import DistanceMetric

metric = DistanceMetric.get_metric('manhattan')
manhattan_data = metric.pairwise(reduced_subsample_data.values)

mds = MDS(n_components=2, max_iter=100, dissimilarity='precomputed', n_jobs=2, n_init=2)
mds_transformed = mds.fit_transform(reduced_subsample_data)
mds_transformed

I had to reduce the amount of datapoints. However, the amount of time needed to process the data (aproximately 7032 datapoints) was too long and therefore the processing had to be cancelled prematurely. Therefore I tried to use a precomputed distance matrix where the distance metric is based on the manhattan distance. This resulted in a faster execution time (approximately 3 minutes). The resulting plot based on this computations data shows a strong structure stretching the concentrated datapoints out. This might be based on the fact that the plot in the 3-D space also shows a slight stretch along the dimension 'weeks worked in a year'.

Due to the use of the precalculation of the distance (using the manhattan distance), this result might be no longer a usable 2-D representation of the 3-D data. Also, I have to admit, I am not certain, if I used the preprocessing correctly.

Isomap¶

One of the earliest approaches to manifold learning is the Isomap algorithm, short for Isometric Mapping. Isomap can be viewed as an extension of Multi-dimensional Scaling (MDS) or Kernel PCA. Isomap seeks a lower-dimensional embedding which maintains geodesic distances between all points. Isomap can be performed with the object Isomap. (Source: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/manifold.html#isomap)

In [ ]:
from sklearn.manifold import Isomap
from scipy import sparse

sparse_data = sparse.csr_array(reduced_subsample_data.values)

isomap = Isomap(n_components=2, n_neighbors=100)
isomap_transformed = isomap.fit_transform(sparse_data)
isomap_transformed

As with the 3-D plot, it can be observed that projected to a lower deimenstion while keeping the distance measure (geodesic distance in this case), the clumping remains. Since there was no discernable grouping in the 3-D plot, it can't be observed in a lower dimension either. However, the structure seems to thin out to the right probably due to the fact that in the 3-D plot there is also a concentration of datapoints in the higher value ranges of the dimension 'weeks worked in a year'.

t-SNE¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE

tsne_transformed = TSNE(n_components=2, learning_rate='auto',
                   init='random').fit_transform(subsample_data.values)
In [ ]:
df_subset = pd.DataFrame()
df_subset['tsne-2d-one'] = tsne_transformed[:,0]
df_subset['tsne-2d-two'] = tsne_transformed[:,1]

plt.figure(figsize=(16,10))
sns.scatterplot(
    x="tsne-2d-one", y="tsne-2d-two",
    palette=sns.color_palette("hls", 10),
    data=df_subset,
    legend="full",
    alpha=0.3
)
Out[ ]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='tsne-2d-one', ylabel='tsne-2d-two'>

The plot of the result from the tsne-transformation is rather unexpected. But again, there seems to be a concentration of datapoints in the lower area of the plot corresponding to the concentration of datapoints in the higher value range of 'weeks worked in year'. Even though it is an irrelevant observation from a data science point of view, this plot seems to be the most beautiful. The dispersion is rather wide. Ther is considerably less clumping. Some unexpected patterns also emerged. These patterns can't be observed in the 3-D plot. T-SNE seems to tend to cluster the datapoints due to how it deals with similarities (moving points closer to similar points, similarity is based on probabilities instead of euclidean distances and therefore the euclidean distance is not preserved).
